Evaluation of the IoT LoRaWAN solution for
distributed measurement applications
Mattia Rizzi, Paolo Ferrari, Alessandra Flammini, Emiliano Sisinni
Dept. of Information Engineering University of Brescia Brescia, Italy
emiliano.sisinni@unibs.it
Abstract— Internet of Things (IoT) is based on data collection, where billions of sensors sample the real world; in other words, the IoT includes a giant distributed measurement system. A question still requiring an answer is: are the IoT technologies usable to enhance traditional measurement systems, since they have been developed for a very similar objective? In this paper the use of a LoRa technology, originally developed for IoT, is investigated with the aim of implementing distributed measurement systems. After the conclusion that LoRa (Long Range) and LoRaWAN (LoRa Wide Area Network) architectures show a good match with measurement systems, the paper focuses on the characterization of time related performance indicators that are important for distributed systems. The experimental results show: the capability of low cost transceiver to schedule the transmission of frames with a standard uncertainty less than 3 µs; and an acceptable long term clock stability (Allan Deviation) of commercial available devices (nodes and packet forwarders) for application like smart metering, structural health monitoring and process industry.
Keywords—Wireless sensor networks, chirp spread spectrum, real time, industrial automation.
I. INTRODUCTION
The Internet of Things (IoT) is one of the key technologies of the present and the near future, as discussed in recent market surveys (e.g. consider the recent Gartner Symposium/ITxpo 2016, just to mention one) and scientific world [1]. Smart and connected things are transforming themselves from stand-alone devices to parts of collaborative systems. Clearly, this growth is also driven by the fact that smart objects are cheaper and more powerful than in the recent past.
Actually, the real basis of the IoT is the pervasive, continuous and efficient data collection. Data are stored, aggregated and analyzed by analytics (based on cloud computing) to extract more information [2][3]. In other words, the set of sensors, devices and storage systems, by which the IoT is composed of, is very similar to a giant distributed measurement systems.
Typically, a huge amount of information is collected from a very large number of smart devices with a low sampling rate (from few times per hour to few times per day) and stored in the cloud. Moreover, slow sampling allows the implementation of specialized transmission technologies oriented to scalability, like the wireless sensor networks [4]. To be precise, the availability of an ideal, IoT oriented, wireless communication technology for covering very large areas (thus reducing the number of base stations), with adequate transfer rate (up to tens of kbps), and with a long node lifetime (even if battery supplied), is still an open research. Smart cities, smart grids, pollution monitoring, transportation, remote health care application fields are waiting such kind of technology [5][6][7][8], and also the new Industry 4.0 may be heavily based on it [9][10][11].
Summarizing, the IoT systems are similar to a distributed measurement system (DMS) and IoT world is pushing new technologies. However, IoT systems have never been characterized in light of DMS requirements (as uncertainty and timestamps). This situation opens some questions for instrumentation and measurement scientists, for instance: are new IoT technologies usable to realize or replace specialized (private) distributed measurement systems? In other, more general, words: are the new IoT technologies able to provide satisfactory measurement performance?
In this paper, Low Power Wide Area Networks (LPWAN) are considered as a viable solution for large scale distributed measurement systems. In particular, the very new wireless technology LoRaWAN technology is evaluated, which is the open standard LPWAN than can boast the largest number of already deployed pilot studies. It is based on LoRa radios from Semtech Corporation, is considered. Originally conceived for IoT slow sampling rate, long distance communication, it has good scalability, cellular architecture, and central coordination function. This paper investigates the use of LoRa from the perspective of distributed measurement systems and applications. Then, the paper tries for the first time (according to the best authors’ knowledge) to experimentally evaluate physical and data link layers capability of LoRaWAN, mainly considering time related performance indicators.
The paper is structured as follows. In the Section II, the paper objective is presented and key aspects of the LoRaWAN proposal are discussed against the more general concept of distributed measurement system. In Section III some details of LoRaWAN

technology are given in order to highlight the fundamental limits. In Section IV, the normative constraints for the use of this wireless technology are discussed. Finally, in Section V, the experimental setup is described and the experiment results are presented.
II. DISTRIBUTED MEASUREMENT SYSTEMS AND IOT
A distributed measurement system (DMS) allows to collect measurements from several sensors/transducers deployed on the field connected by means of a (digital) network for further processing and visualization [12][13]. In particular, DMS offer great benefits over traditional approaches when several (possibly hard-to-reach) measuring points are distributed on a large area. Industrial applications are among first adopters of such an approach, since the introduction of fieldbuses [XX]. More recently, the smart grid concept disrupts the power distribution leveraging on DMS for controlling power flows [XX]. Obviously, despite all these application domains share a common arrangement, communication requirements can vary greatly depending on the considered use case. Several figure of merits (FoM) exist for comparing DMS performance. Since a DMS is involved with time series collection, time-related FoMs as refresh time, latency and required time synchronization accuracy are particularly meaningful. Interesting to note, other FoM as the typical frame size or the number of nodes per access point affect or are depending on time-related FoMs (e.g., the throughput). For sake of completeness, TABLE I has been completed starting from data available in literature [14].

