Fig. 4. Measurement setup for the characterization of the transmisison uncertainty (SETUP I).
Fig. 5 and TABLE IV show the measurement results. Notably, the latency strictly depends on the symbol time of the selected SF. The measured latency has a randomly spike of about 8 µs. The spike amplitude is not affected by the SF and it’s probably related to the internal processing of SX1272. Since at the highest rate (SF = 7) the discrete position of the instantaneous frequency jump inside the chirp symbol has a resolution of TC/2SF  8 µs, the achievable level of uncertainty is close to the limit of the LoRa modulation.
TABLE IV shows the statistics of the measured latency, with a standard deviation of about 1.4 µs for both SFs. The distribution of the measurements is not Gaussian due to the occasional spike already mentioned. As previously discussed, the uncertainty measured using SETUP I represents the uncertainty of the transmission of a LoRa frame respect to an external trigger signal. In an application involving a device distributing a “Beacon” (i.e. frequency distribution), the measured uncertainty would be a limiting factor.

